  "prompt": "How do you determine the unit of quantity of electricity?",
  "response": "In electrical engineering and physics, the fundamental unit of electric charge is the Coulomb (C). The Coulomb is defined as the quantity of electric charge transferred by a current of 1 ampere in 1 second. \n\nHere are some key points about measuring electricity quantity:\n\n1. Unit of Electric Charge: Coulomb (C)\n- Represents the total amount of electric charge\n- Named after French physicist Charles-Augustin de Coulomb\n\n2. Related Units:\n- Ampere (A): Current measurement (charge per second)\n- Relationship: 1 Coulomb = 1 Ampere \u00d7 1 second\n\n3. Calculation Methods:\n- Charge (Q) = Current (I) \u00d7 Time (t)\n- Q = I \u00d7 t\n\n4. Smaller Units:\n- Millicoulomb (mC): 1/1000 of a Coulomb\n- Microcoulomb (\u00b5C): 1/1,000,000 of a Coulomb\n\n5. Practical Measurement:\n- Electrical meters\n- Charge measurement devices\n- Specialized scientific instruments\n\nThe Coulomb provides a standardized way to quantify electric charge across different electrical systems and applications.",
